source.Name: Total population
source.Summary: Population: Total population and distribution by age and sex estimated to be consistent with the population by age and sex of the (a) 1969, 1982, 1992, 2002, 2012, 2022 censuses; (b) adjusted for under/over count; (c) adjusted for age heaping; (d) adjusted for under enumeration of children under age 15; (e) 1987, 1997 ICDS and 1994, 2005-2006 DHS survey estimates; (f) official estimates through 2023; (g) only total population for 1956, 1961 censuses; and with estimates of the subsequent trends in fertility, mortality and international migration.

source.Name: Total fertility rate
source.Summary: Fertility: Total fertility rate and age pattern of fertility based on: (a) birth-histories data from the 1984 RHS and 1988, 1994, 1999, 2005-2006, 2010-2011, 2015 DHS and 2009, 2014, 2019 MICS; (b) births in the household in the preceding 12 (or 24) months classified by age of mother from the 1969, 1982, 1992, 2002, 2012, 2022 censuses and 1984 RHS and 2017 ICDS; (c) adjusted fertility using Brass P/F ratio method (or variants) with data on children ever born and births in the preceding 12 (or 24/36) months, both classified by age of mother, from the 1969, 1982 censuses; (d) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1982, 1992, 2002, 2012 censuses and 1997 ICDS; (e) indirect estimates obtained from stable population assumption; (f) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 1969, 1982, 1992, 2002 censuses and 1984 RHS and 1987, 1997, 2017 ICDS and 1988, 1994, 1999, 2005-2006, 2010-2011, 2015 DHS and 2009, 2014, 2019 MICS. In addition, the (a) official estimates of age-specific fertility rates through 2005; (b) registered births classified by age of mother and the underlying female population by age through 1979; (c) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1969 Census; (d) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 2012 Census have been considered.

source.Name: Life expectancy at birth
source.Summary: Overall Mortality: Life expectancy at birth and age pattern of mortality based on: (a) registered deaths by age and sex available through 2012; (b) adjusted for underreporting of infant and child deaths; (c) adult deaths adjusted for underregistration using death distribution methods; (d) mortality rates for older ages were adjusted; (e) The demographic impact of AIDS has been factored into the mortality estimates; (f) estimates using HIV/AIDS model life tables and estimates of under-five mortality (5q0) and adult mortality (45q15) with UNAIDS estimates of adult HIV prevalence, and ART coverage for children and adults. Mortality rates for Spectrum were calculated by removing AIM's estimates of HIV-related mortality from all-cause mortality rate estimates published in the 2024 revision of the World Population Prospects.

source.Name: Age Mortality
source.Summary: Adult and Old Age Mortality: Estimates derived from: (a) deaths by age and sex available from Register through 2012; (b) adjusted for underregistration; (c) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 2017 ICDS and 2022 Census; (d) recent household deaths adjusted at adult ages for underregistration using death distribution methods; (e) siblings deaths from the 1994, 1999, 2005-2006, 2010-2011, 2015 DHS and 2014, 2019 MICS; (f) maternal orphanhood from the 1982, 1992, 2002, 2012 censuses and 1994, 1999, 2005-2006, 2010-2011, 2015 DHS and 1997 ICDS and 2009, 2014, 2019 MICS; (g) paternal orphanhood from the 1982, 1992, 2002, 2012 censuses and 1994, 1999, 2005-2006, 2010-2011, 2015 DHS and 1997 ICDS and 2009, 2014, 2019 MICS; (h) indirect estimates of male adult mortality based on female widowhood data from the 1982, 1992, 2002, 2012 censuses and 1987, 1997, 2017 ICDS and 1988, 1994, 1999, 2005-2006, 2010-2011, 2015 DHS and 2009, 2014 MICS; (i) intercensal survivorship from successive census age distributions; (j) estimates of under-five, adult and old age mortality. In addition, the (a) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 1992, 2002, 2012 censuses and 1997 ICDS and 2005-2006 DHS; (b) indirect estimates of female adult mortality based on male widowhood data from the 1982, 1992, 2002, 2012 censuses and 1987, 1997, 2017 ICDS and 1988, 1994, 1999, 2005-2006, 2010-2011, 2015 DHS and 2009, 2014 MICS have been considered.

source.Name: Infant/child mortality
source.Summary: Child Mortality: Under-five mortality based on: (a) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 1988, 1994, 1999, 2010-2011, 2015 DHS and 2009, 2014, 2019 MICS; (b) indirect estimates from data on children ever born and surviving from the 1969, 1982, 1992, 2002 censuses and 1984 RHS and 1987, 1997 ICDS; (c) International estimates used up to 2021. In addition, the (a) registered infant and child deaths through 2002; (b) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 2005-2006 DHS and 2008 ICDS; (c) recent household deaths from the 1992, 2002, 2012, 2022 censuses and 1997, 2017 ICDS and 2005-2006 DHS have been considered.

source.Name: International migration
source.Summary: Migration: International migration based on: (a) information on foreign-born populations from censuses and registers from major countries of destination; (b) information on the number of migrant workers or about labor migration; (c) estimates derived as the differences between overall population growth and natural increase; (d) UNHCR statistics on the number of refugees in the main countries of asylum.
